data.content:
## .NET 8 Migration: `TimedExecutor`

### Breaking Changes

| .NET Framework | .NET 8 |
|---|---|
| `Thread.Abort()` | **Throws `PlatformNotSupportedException`** |
| `Thread.ResetAbort()` | **Throws `PlatformNotSupportedException`** |
| `ThreadAbortException` | Never thrown by runtime |

### Migrated Code — Using `CancellationToken` + `Task`

```csharp
public class TimedExecutor
{
    public T ExecuteWithTimeout<T>(Func<CancellationToken, T> work, TimeSpan timeout)
    {
        using var cts = new CancellationTokenSource(timeout);

        var task = Task.Run(() => work(cts.Token), cts.Token);

        try
        {
            // Block until completion or timeout.
            // Task.Wait throws AggregateException on cancellation/fault.
            task.Wait(cts.Token);
            return task.Result;
        }
        catch (OperationCanceledException) when (cts.IsCancellationRequested)
        {
            throw new TimeoutException(
                $"Operation exceeded {timeout.TotalSeconds}s timeout");
        }
    }

    // Async overload — preferred in modern code
    public async Task<T> ExecuteWithTimeoutAsync<T>(
        Func<CancellationToken, Task<T>> work, TimeSpan timeout)
    {
        using var cts = new CancellationTokenSource(timeout);

        try
        {
            return await work(cts.Token);
        }
        catch (OperationCanceledException) when (cts.IsCancellationRequested)
        {
            throw new TimeoutException(
                $"Operation exceeded {timeout.TotalSeconds}s timeout");
        }
    }
}
```

### Usage

```csharp
var executor = new TimedExecutor();

// Sync — work must observe the token
var result = executor.ExecuteWithTimeout(ct =>
{
    for (int i = 0; i < 1_000_000; i++)
    {
        ct.ThrowIfCancellationRequested(); // cooperative check
        // ... do work ...
    }
    return 42;
}, TimeSpan.FromSeconds(5));

// Async — preferred
var asyncResult = await executor.ExecuteWithTimeoutAsync(async ct =>
{
    // Most I/O APIs accept CancellationToken natively
    return await httpClient.GetStringAsync(url, ct);
}, TimeSpan.FromSeconds(10));
```

### Key Pitfalls

**1. Cancellation is cooperative, not preemptive.**
`Thread.Abort()` forcibly killed threads. `CancellationToken` requires the work to **check the token**. If you call unmanaged code or a library that ignores tokens, it won't stop.

**2. Legacy "fire-and-forget" workaround for uncooperative code:**
```csharp
// Last resort — the work runs to completion but you stop waiting.
// Leaks the thread/task if work never finishes. Use sparingly.
public T ExecuteWithTimeoutUncooperative<T>(Func<T> work, TimeSpan timeout)
{
    var task = Task.Run(work);

    if (task.Wait(timeout))
        return task.Result;

    // Task is abandoned — not killed
    throw new TimeoutException(
        $"Operation exceeded {timeout.TotalSeconds}s timeout");
}
```

**3. `Thread.ResetAbort()` has no equivalent** — there's nothing to reset because abort never happens.

**4. Exception handling change:** The old code caught `ThreadAbortException` specially. In .NET 8, use `OperationCanceledException` as the cancellation signal instead.

**5. Signature is a breaking change.** Callers must update from `Func<T>` → `Func<CancellationToken, T>`. If you need backward compatibility:
```csharp
// Adapter for legacy callers (no cooperative cancellation)
public T ExecuteWithTimeout<T>(Func<T> work, TimeSpan timeout)
    => ExecuteWithTimeout(_ => work(), timeout);
```
This compiles but the work **cannot be cancelled early** — it only times out the wait.

### Summary

| Concern | Recommendation |
|---|---|
| Preferred pattern | `async` + `CancellationToken` |
| Cooperative work | Check `ct.ThrowIfCancellationRequested()` in loops |
| Uncooperative work | Abandon the task (accept the leak) or run in a separate **process** |
| Hard kill needed | Use `Process.Kill()` on a child process — only reliable preemptive stop in .NET 8 |
